text=:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity%0a:Essential: {Category.MorphosyntacticDiversity$:essential}%0a:Title: Giving an exam in Indian English%0a:Author: Mihir_D%0a:Section: A%0a:Completed: 16.04.2021 - 08:24%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210421-175016-168040#%0a* [-21.04.2021 - 10:50-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210421-175016-168040#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aIndian English has several instances of verbs being used as they are in native languages like Hindi. %0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aStandard American and British English have conventions for using particular verbs in particular contexts. Due to direct translations from native languages such as Hindi, alternative verbs are common in Indian English.%0a%0aSome examples:%0a%0aStandard English: "take/write/sit for" a test%0aIndian English (IndE) also has: "give" a test%0aIn Hindi, this phrase could translate to "परीक्षा दो", where "दो" means "give".%0a%0aStandard English: "turn off" a light%0aIndE also has: "close" a light ("off" a light is used as well)%0aIn Hindi, this phrase could translate to "लाइट बंद करें", where "बंद" means "close".%0a%0aStandard English: I "live" here%0aIndE also has: I "stay" here%0aIn Marathi, this phrase would translate to "मी इथे राहातो", where "राहातो" usually means "I stay"%0a%0aSimilar literal translations exist for "keep" (IndE) to mean "put" and "cut" (IndE) to mean "hang up (a call)". Idioms are also translated leading to "eating my brains/head" (मेरा दिमाग खा रहा है) being used when someone is bugging you.%0a%0aAn example of a non-verb being literally translated is "good name", meaning "शुभ नाम" which is how people politely ask for full names as opposed to a nickname.%0a%0aThese variations are commonly used and accepted, as English is often a second language for many Indians, so many try to translate directly from their native languages. These variations still make sense even for a non IndE speaker, so there is not much of a barrier to understanding. Many IndE speakers (like my parents) use some of these constructions without even realizing it. %0a%0aOn the other hand, there are also American English constructions that are particularly confusing for IndE speakers, such as "the alarm went off" to mean the alarm turned on.%0a%0aSource: https://www.ling.upenn.edu/~jason2/papers/ienglish.htm%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
