ng you.%0a%3c %0a%3c An example of a non-verb being literally translated is "good name", meaning "शुभ नाम" which is how people politely ask for full names as opposed to a nickname.%0a%3c %0a%3c These variations are commonly used and accepted, as English is often a second language for many Indians, so many try to translate directly from their native languages. These variations still make sense even for a non IndE speaker, so there is not much of a barrier to understanding. Many IndE speakers (like my parents) use some of these constructions without even realizing it. %0a%3c %0a%3c On the other hand, there are also American English constructions that are particularly confusing for IndE speakers, such as "the alarm went off" to mean the alarm turned on.%0a%3c %0a%3c Source: https://www.ling.upenn.edu/~jason2/papers/ienglish.htm%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
